<DOC><DOCNO> AP880415-0177 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2031EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Egypt-Tanks     04-15 0213</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Egypt-Tanks,200</SECOND><HEAD>Pentagon Asks Congressional Approval For $2 Billion Egypt TankDeal</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Pentagon formally requested congressionalapproval Friday for a $2 billion co-production deal that wouldallow Egypt to build M-1A1 Abrams tanks.   The arms transaction, disclosed several months ago byadministration officials, calls for the sale of 555 M-1A1 tanks. Asmany as 540 of them could be built on a new assembly line to beconstructed in Egypt.   Congress will now have 30 days to veto the deal should it wishto do so.   The Pentagon, in notifying Congress it had approved thetransaction, argued Egypt ``needs an advanced tank to ensure thestability of the existing regional military balance, especiallyvis-a-vis Libya.''   ``The sale of this equipment and support will not adverselyaffect the basic military balance in the region,'' the Pentagonsaid.   ``This sale will contribute to the foreign policy and nationalsecurity of the United States by helping to improve the security ofa friendly country which has been and continues to be an importantforce for stability and peace in the Middle East.''   The Pentagon said the U.S. Army would be responsible foroverseeing the transaction and that the prime contractor would bethe General Dynamics Land Services Corp. of Warren, Mich.</TEXT></DOC>